Short-term effects of national-level natural resource rents on life expectancy: 
A cross-country panel data analysis.

Lyatuu I(1)(2)(3), Loss G(2)(3), Farnham A(2)(3), Winkler MS(2)(3), Fink 
G(2)(3).

Author information:
(1)Ifakara Health Institute, Dar es Salaam, United Republic of Tanzania.
(2)Department of Epidemiology and Public Health, Swiss Tropical and Public 
Health Institute, Basel, Switzerland.
(3)University of Basel, Basel, Switzerland.

While a substantial amount of literature addresses the relationship between 
natural resources and economic growth, relatively little is known regarding the 
relationship between natural resource endowment and health at the population 
level. We construct a 5-year cross-country panel to assess the impact of natural 
resource rents on changes in life expectancy at birth as a proxy indicator for 
population health during the period 1970-2015. To estimate the causal effects of 
interest, we use global commodity prices as instrumental variables for natural 
resource rent incomes in two-stage-least squares regressions. Controlling for 
country and year fixed effects, we show that each standard deviation increase in 
resource rents results in life expectancy increase of 6.72% (CI: 2.01%, 11.44%). 
This corresponds to approximately one additional year of life expectancy gained 
over five years. We find a larger positive effect of rents on life expectancy in 
sub-Saharan Africa (SSA) compared to other world regions. We do not find 
short-term effects of rents on economic growth, but show that increases in 
resource rents result in sizeable increases in government revenues in the short 
run, which likely translate into increased spending across government sectors. 
This suggests that natural resources can help governments finance health and 
other development-oriented programs needed to improve population health.

